subject: Project 1 Help
content: Hi, . My name is Seta and I am in your EECS 280 class. . I checked my grade this morning for Project 1 and I was a little surprised that I had failed so many of the private tests, as I thought I was pretty thorough in my testing in my work on this project. In an effort to learn from my mistakes and be able to improve on the next project, I went to office hours today and met with a GSI. When she looked at my code in the Autograder, she actually told me that she herself didn't understand why I was graded so low and she couldn't identify more than one issue that would have had me fail so many of the cases, and said that I had accounted for almost all edge cases in my testing Clearly, I'm missing something, but for the sake of learning and trying not to make the same mistakes for the next project, could you please find time to go over with me what I did wrong on this project / how to improve my test case writing? Let me know when you are available, or if someone could look at it over email / office hours. . . Thank you very much, . Seta Hagopian
i_answer: I took a look at your AG submission.  Here's what I found:. . For median:  Looks like you're not 0-indexing.  Recall vectors are 0-indexed.. For mode:  Consider the case {2, 2, 3, 3, 3}.  Your code doesn't the case if the mode is the greatest value in the vector by just one greater frequency.. . For percentile:  Based on Appendix A of the percentile formula, v must be sorted for the formula to work.  You cannot assume that v is sorted when it is passed in and you don't sort v in the function.. . For summarize:  Your function looks to operate based on the assumption that v is sorted.  Unfortunately there is no requirement for v to be sorted for the function and you don't sort your vector in the function implementation.. . For count: There is no requirement that v isn't empty, i.e. your assert statement will fail if v is empty.. . For testing in the future, I recommend fully taking a look at the RME of the functions you're implementing and testing cases that almost break your requires clause, i.e. test cases that fulfill your requires clause but barely fulfill it.  Also make sure to not make assumptions on the arguments of your function beyond what's stated in the requires clause.  If you wish to discuss testing strategies or project strategies with someone, I recommend going to proffice hours this week if you have the time (or the normal OH queue if you unable to attend any of the proffice hour times).  The professors have been teaching this class for many semesters and have a lot of advice for how to write good test cases and how to approach the future projects.  Hope this helps.

subject: problem：Test real data
content: I test my code by stats_test.cpp , main_test_data.tsv and other special conditions. They all work. But when I test the real data, it just like stopping at summarize but without any bug or errors. What should I do?
i_answer: I suspect there isn't really an error but rather your program is taking a long time to run, i.e. if you let your code run and come back in an hour or two then it'll probably finish.  Based on follow ups it sounds like you are using a double loop in summarize which is probably what is causing this timing issue.  With the real data set, the data vector is very large (VERY large) so you're summarize function runs in $$O(n^2)$$ which isn't ideal for large data sets.. . That being said, for 280, we don't expect your code to run in under 30 seconds for a data set of size 4002 in this project (We leave writing super time efficient programs for eecs 281).  So rest assured we won't run your code on a data set that large on the AG for this project.  For future projects, we will specify in the spec if we plan on running your code with large data sets and tips/tricks for if your code is taking too long.

subject: Summarize Output
content: Hello! I am having some trouble with my summarize function. When I test main_test_data.tsv on my terminal, it only outputs . 6: 1 . 7: 1. 8: 1. 10: 1. I'm not sure why it skips 9: 1 entirely. I tried setting breakpoints, writing more tests, and stepping into my code but I still can't catch the bug.
i_answer: I think the part that is causing this is your if statement if (i == v.size() - 1). When you reach i = 4, Element = 9 and frequency = 1.. Because i = 4 and v.size() = 5, you enter that if statement and then you enter the else statement that pushes back v.at(i), so you never push 9 back into the vector.

content: I thought I was pretty much done but then I discovered my mode function is giving the wrong output despite it somehow passing the autograder for the public test cases. I'll make sure only instructors can see this. This is a whole lot and I'm not sure how else I'm supposed to find mode taking into account if all numbers in the vector are the same aside from the method I use. I need help figuring out a better way of getting the right output since the project is due today at 8pm and I'm very close to finishing.. . sort(v); int current_count = 1; double current_num = 0; double most_num = 0; int most_count = 0; for (std::size_t i = 0; i < v.size(); ++i) {  for (std::size_t j = 0; j < v.size(); ++j) {   if (v[j] == v[i]) {    current_num = v[j];    current_count += 1;   }   if (v[j] == v[v.size() - 1]) {    most_num = v[j];    j = v.size();    i = v.size();   }      else if (v[j] != v[i] && v[i] == v[0]) {    most_num = current_num;    most_count = current_count;    current_num = 0;    current_count = 0;    i = j;    j = v.size();   }   if (v[i] > v[0] && v[j] != v[i]) {    if (current_count > most_count) {     most_num = current_num;     most_count = current_count;     current_num = 0;     current_count = 0;     i = j;     j = v.size();    }.    }  }.  } return most_num;  }

subject: Summarize in main

You can check this by setting a breakpoint with your debugger and inspecting the vector's contents (as well as its structure).. . If everything looks right with the vector, remember accessing elements of a multidimensional vector will look something like vec[i][j] where i affects which vector you are accessing and j affects which element of vector i is accessed.

i_answer: Some IDEs will allow this to compile (as well as some compilers like `clang` if you're on a mac). As the followup below suggests, compilation via the terminal with the Makefile given with the project should bring up an error if you're using `g++` (though again if you're on a mac it will be `clang` pretending to be `g++` and you still may not get an error.. . It turns out for this project the autograder is configured to specifically ignore the warning that comes up for signed vs. unsigned comparison, though that isn't guaranteed to be the case for other projects.

subject: Floating Point Comparison Mode
content: HI, I was wondering if two entries in the vector inputed into our mode functions differ by only 1*10^-7, would our mode function be correct if it classified them as the same value? For example, could I say that in {1, 1.0000000001}, the number 1 appears twice and thus, is the mode?. . Thanks
i_answer: No, in this case the numbers would be considered different for the purposes of the `mode()` function (or the frequency counts in `summarize()`). For mode you can use `==` to compare numbers.. . (This is distinct from places where we consider equality in a "close enough" sense, such as comparing output in test cases for functions that do arithmetic on the numbers.)

subject: Summarize function output
content: Screen_Shot_2021-09-15_at_10.54.22_PM.png. When I output my summarize function, it ends up leaving out the last value for some reason. When I change the loop to increment from i < v.size() to i < v.size() + 1, I also end up getting an error since it indexes outside of the given vector. How would I get that last vector of values to appear?
i_answer: Think about what happens when you reach the last value in your vector. You never hit a statement that adds this to the vector because you never run into the case that adds the value if it does not equal the previous/next value - you simply run out of items and the loop exits. However, this value along with its frequency should still be saved in whatever variables you are saving them in. You may need another push_back outside of your loop to get the last value into the summarize vector.

subject: Test Case Quality Graded?
content: Will the autograder somehow grade the quality of our test cases, or do we make test cases more for us to know that our code works?
i_answer: The autograder will run "buggy" versions of stats.cpp against your test cases. If your test cases catch the errors, you get the points for the errors caught.We have you write test cases because (1) it helps you to test and check that your code works, and (2) it's a crucial skill to learn, because when you start working or doing your own projects, you won't have an autograder to check if your program works, just your test cases.. . subject: Can I use vector.at(int index) to access the element in a vector
content: When I viewed the specification, I noticed that it uses the vector[int index] to access an element in a vector. However, is that fine if I use vector.at(int index) to access the element in a vector? Are there any potential problems to use this method?
i_answer: Both ways to access a value in the vector will work identically. The only difference is that the `[]` operator will return undefined behavior when you try to index an element outside of the range of the vector, while the `.at()` function will return an `out_of_range` exception. This makes no difference as both will fail if you try to access an element outside of the range.

subject: main public test valgrind
content: . this is an error from the main test valgrind portion. What does this mean?
i_answer: When diagnosing this issue:. 1==101== Invalid read of size 82==101== at 0x404FD5: percentile(std::vector<double, std::allocator<double> >, double) (stats.cpp:158)4==101== by 0x402C59: main (main.cpp:54). . We can gather some key information from the error message. . 1. Invalid read of size 8. --> doubles are (normally) 8 bytes. So this means we are trying to access an "invalid" double. Or in other words, we are accessing data that is malformed, not initialized, or that we are not "allowed" to access. Often this is because we are indexing out of bounds. 2. percentile(std::vector<double, std::allocator<double> >, double) (stats.cpp:158) --> This is where the error is occurring. In your percentile function on line 158 of stats.cpp. . . With a location and a reason, diagnosing and solving the issue becomes less obfuscated. Make sure all of your indices will always fall within the bounds of the vector you are indexing into

subject: Stdev -nan
content: I am currently testing my standard deviation function and it keeps returning nan (not a number). In OH I was told this could be because of a divide by zero or a negative under the sqrt. while I found one of these errors in my code, as well as realized I was starting from zero and not from 1, I am still getting nan as my value in my test. Also in EECS 183 it was acceptable to post code to Piazza if the visibility was set to instructors only, so I am assuming that is also the case here, however if it is not then I will of course take this post down.. .
i_answer: check out the line you have that says. . double var = 1/x - 1;. Since 1 is an int and x is an int, then your compiler will evaluate 1/x to be an int.  In your case, nan if x = 0 (divide by zero), 1 if x = 1, and 0 if x > 1.  I'm guessing that when you are running your code, v is a non empty vector that has more than one element.  So then 1/x will evaluate to 0 and then var = 0 - 1=  -1 .  Later on, it looks to be that when assigning a value to 'stand', you end up with a negative under the sqrt.. . To have 1/x specifically be evaluated to a double, then try doing 1.0/x.  Adding the '.0' will tell the compiler to evaluate 1.0/x into a double.

subject: Standard Deviation Always Zero
content: Hey,. . I've been having this weird error where the standard deviation always shows as zero. As you can see in the terminal output, the summation works as expected, however the coefficient (1/(v.size() -1)) always = 0. I'm not exactly sure why why this is, because I have it set to type double and v.size() = 5. If possible, can you please help point me in the right direction? Thank you.. .
i_answer: Try setting coefficient to 1.0/(v.size() - 1); i.e.. . double coefficient = 1.0/(v.size() - 1);. Though you set the type of `coefficient' to be a double, the values you use to initialize that variable are represented as ints/size_t's (not floating point values) and so the compiler treats 1/(v.size() - 1) as an int, rounds down it's floating point value, and sets coefficient to that int.

i_answer: This type of valgrind error means you are reading data out of the bounds of data you are supposed to have access to (i.e. outside the bounds of a vector). It is possible that your code functions correctly still on your personal machine, but this type of error can lead to something called undefined behavior which can have unpredictable results. I would suggest looking at your code again (you can find the file and line number of the error towards the top of the valgrind output) and think about how you can maintain correct behavior on that line while ensuring you don't access out of bounds.

subject: (-0.2 == -0.2) is false ?!
content: I am confused about this code. I don't know why I am getting assertion failure. . Oh, by the way, I hope this doesn't count as sharing code. . . Any idea how to fix this?
i_answer: These two values look like -0.2, but they both have tiny rounding errors. If you were to increase the precision of cout to print several more decimal places, you would see some unexpected values about 10 decimal places down. These errors between the two values are different because the separate rounding errors for -1.2 and 1 were added together. I believe some rounding error exists for all floating point values.. . To combat this, use a constant epsilon value (0.00001). Appendix F in the spec page for Project 1 has a section on "floating point comparisons" and explains how to test for equality despite rounding error. Using this method, you find the difference of the two values you're comparing, find its absolute value, then test whether that value is less than epsilon (0.00001).

subject: Error: attempt to subscript container
content: . . Hi, I am getting this error at the moment. I saw another post with the same issue and it said it was a vector index issue, but my code actually worked using another command. . Using this command in the spec led to no errors and my output was correct, I think. (Even for my tests and stats_public test). . g++ -Wall -Werror -pedantic --std=c++11 -g main.cpp stats.cpp p1_library.cpp -o main.exe. however, using . . make main. . g++ --std=c++11 -Wall -Werror -pedantic -g -D_GLIBCXX_DEBUG main.cpp stats.cpp p1_library.cpp -o main.exe. and then . . make test. led to this error below. The error basically only occurs when I use the makefile command (which just has the difference of the "-D_GLIBCXX_DEBUG" part). . .
i_answer: Somewhere in your code, you're indexing a vector with size 3 at the index 3, which is out of bounds. The flag enables debug mode, which warns you about this, as this is **undefined behavior** and will give you garbage data. It might be the case that what this data is doesn't matter (e.g. you're multiplying it by 0), but in other cases, this would cause your code to silently fail.. . I'd recommend you use `std::vector::at` instead of `[]` (e.g. `v.at(3)` instead of `v[3]`), as this will perform bounds-checking and throw an `std::out_of_range` exception when you try to index out of bounds, telling you upfront about the error.

subject: EECS 280 Folder and g++
content: I'm having trouble making the directories go to my EECS 280 folder on my desktop, Ubuntu says the directories I'm making are going to home and my Ubuntu account name but I'm using windows so it should be going to Users and to my desktop. i_answer: Looks like we resolved your issues with g++ in your other post here: @216. . For creating your project folder and files on your Desktop using the terminal, you'll need to navigate to the Windows part of the file system - by default, WSL will open up in your /home directory which is in the Ubuntu part of the file system. To get to your Desktop, you need to navigate to /mnt/c/ - this is where you should go to get to your Windows files. Then you can get to your Desktop by going to Users/[your Windows username]/Desktop. From there you can get to your eecs 280 folder (or make it if you haven't already) on your Desktop.. . Just some general advice too for looking around your files through the terminal:. If you're ever unsure if where you are, run pwd to get your current path - this will show you exactly what folder you're in, and whereIf you're ever unsure about what files there are in your current folder, run ls to list all the files in that folder. I hope this helps!.

subject: Valgrind - "conditional jump or move depends on unitialized variable"
content: I will be posting some of my code in this question. I marked it down to be private to instructors, so it was my understanding that it's allowed in the honor code policy. If not, please feel free to let me know (or just take this post down yourself if you can?).. . I'm trying to get past this error that's keeps coming up when I run Valgrind:. . . . I was recommended to run this command:. . valgrind --tool=memcheck --track-origins=yes <program_path>. Which is why I also have the second statement after the error, "uninitialised value was created by a stack allocation". Here's the code where this problem originates:. . . . Hopefully you can see why I'm getting confused. The line that's getting the error is 26:. . if (v[i] == sumv[j][0]). But as far as I can see, each of the variables here are all clearly initialized: v is the vector passed to the function, sumv is the vector of a vector initialized as empty, i and j are both initialized as equal to 0 in their respective "for-loops". Valgrind seems to think the variable was declared on line 12, which is literally just an open bracket and doesn't include any code. That seems to suggest to me the problem is with v, which is passed into the function in the line before. But, what can I do to make sure v is initialized? Or am I misunderstanding something?. . Thanks for your help.
i_answer: Function parameters should always be initialized, so v should be fine. I think the issue is with sumv. In particular, even though sumv is initialized to be empty, remember that sumv is a vector of vectors, so you need to initialize the outer vector (which you do on line 16) and the inner vectors as well. The inner vectors should be initialized before you add them to sumv, so is there a line where you push back a vector to sumv? I would check that line to make sure that when you add a vector to sumv, all of its elements are initialized.

subject: Very small extra value added to a double that is not intended
content: . I have initialized total to 0.0, then added exactly 75.37 to it and it ends up being the value shown in the image, and is causing tests to fail. Any ideas as to what is going wrong and how to fix it? This only started happening after I added a negative number to the vector, but it was not added to the total at this point.
i_answer: This is OK. Doubles in c++ can experience rounding errors, so even though you are expecting 75.37, you end up with some high precision error. As a result, when we compare doubles we can't use the == operator. Instead, we can check the difference between the expected value and the actual value. If the difference is small enough, it can be considered equal.. . More about this, and examples, can be here found in the spec.

subject: Signed and Unsigned Variable comparison
content: When trying to run my executable I am getting an error that my variable comparison is invalid because one is signed, and one is unsigned, what does this mean?. .
i_answer: int is ‘signed’, meaning it can hold negative and nonnegative values, while size_t is ‘unsigned’, meaning it can only hold nonnegative values. The .size() operator returns a value of type size_t, which holds unsigned values, so it may be best to declare i as type size_t instead of int. When indexing over a vector or array, we are dealing with nonnegative numbers, and thus size_t would be best to use over int..

subject: Error with assertions in stats functions

I was told I could set it up after the implementation too as I could not get it working before.. . error: control reaches end of non-void function [-Werror=return-type]
i_answer: It means that you have a function that has a non-void return type (e.g. `double sum(std::vector v)`), but you are not returning anything. If you changed the `assert(false)` to `assert(true)`, the compiler will look for a return statement at the end of your function body, which it can't find right now. subject: Summarize function clarification
content: can someone help me understand the logic of this function.. . I know that it represents a vector within a vector, and I know that the inner vector is the one defined as vector<double> v.. . however, I have no idea which one is the outer vector, or how to access it.. . I tried stating: summarize(v).push_back(value) for example, but that gives me errors.. . So that kind of ruled out summarize as being the outer vector.. .
i_answer: `vector> summarize(vector v)` means that `summarize` takes a `vector` argument and returns a `vector>`. This means that, inside the function body, you have to create a new `vector>` and return it at the end.. . If you have a `vector> w`, you can use vector methods on `w` to modify the outer vector (e.g. `w.push_back({1, 2, 3})`). For the inner vectors, you must use the vector element access methods (such as `w[idx]` or `w.at(idx)`) to get a specific element, and then you can likewise use the vector methods to modify those (e.g. `w.at(0).push_back(5)`).

subject: A Question about the long chain of code
content: Hi, . . I have a question about this.. . . . Why do we need such a long chain of code in front of the main.exe? What are these "g++" "Wall"  "-Werror" doing?.
i_answer: We're passing options to `g++`, the compiler:. . -   `-Wall` enables all warnings. -   `-Werror` makes all warnings into errors that will abort compilation. -   `--std=c++11` tells the compiler to compile using the C++11 standard. -   `-g` enables extra debugging information for use by debuggers such as GDB. -   `-o main.exe` means the compiler will output the executable as the file `main.exe`. -   `main.cpp`, `stats.cpp`, and `p1_library.cpp` are the source code files to be compiled and linked together. . Reference the man page (`man g++`) for more details.

subject: A Question about this error
content: Hi,. . I have a question about this.. . . why I have this error reported?. . Thank you!
i_answer: Currently, your `sum` function has `assert(false)` in its body, probably indicating that you haven't implemented it yet. `assert` takes a boolean expression, which, if evaluates to false, will abort execution. You can make this error go away by implementing `sum` or, for now, returning a dummy value such as `0`.

subject: CAEN make sync shortcut not activating

If the 'make sync' command doesn't work on your local terminal, it may be a whitespace issue.  Make sure the 'rsync' line is 1 tabbed over.  Sometimes your IDE may replace a tab with spaces instead, and a way to check if it's a proper tab is to put your cursor on the left of 'rsync' and hit the right arrow key.  If your cursor takes you to the left margin, then it's a proper tab, if it doesn't then the tab got replaced with spaces.

subject: Mega Tutorial VS Code
content: I am currently at the compile portion of the visual studio code setup and I noticed as I typed in "make stats_tests.exe" to my terminal, I saw c++ as the first thing that popped up and not g++: . . If you really want to use g++, then you can install the real g++ compiler through homebrew (brew), but it is unnecessary.. . [OS X 10.9 gcc links to clang- StackOverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19535422/os-x-10-9-gcc-links-to-clang). . Notice how it says "Apple clang..." below.. . ```. $ g++ --version  . Configured with: --prefix=/Library/Developer/CommandLineTools/usr --with-gxx-include-dir=/Library/Developer/CommandLineTools/SDKs/MacOSX.sdk/usr/include/c++/4.2.1  . Apple clang version 13.0.0 (clang-1300.0.29.3)  . Target: x86\_64-apple-darwin21.0.0  . Thread model: posix  . InstalledDir: /Library/Developer/CommandLineTools/usr/bin. ```

I followed the instructions previous to this step and everything ran fine on my computer. Does anyone know how to fix this?. . (base) Sophies-MacBook-Pro-3:p1-stats sophiemarcotte$ make clean. rm -rvf *.exe *~ *.out *.dSYM *.stackdump. (base) Sophies-MacBook-Pro-3:p1-stats sophiemarcotte$ make stats_tests.exe. x86_64-apple-darwin13.4.0-clang++ -march=core2 -mtune=haswell -mssse3 -ftree-vectorize -fPIC -fPIE -fstack-protector-strong -O2 -pipe -stdlib=libc++ -fvisibility-inlines-hidden -std=c++14 -fmessage-length=0 stats_tests.cpp stats.cpp p1_library.cpp -o stats_tests.exe. In file included from stats_tests.cpp:18:. In file included from ./stats.h:12:. In file included from /Users/sophiemarcotte/opt/miniconda3/bin/../include/c++/v1/vector:265:. In file included from /Users/sophiemarcotte/opt/miniconda3/bin/../include/c++/v1/iosfwd:90:. /Users/sophiemarcotte/opt/miniconda3/bin/../include/c++/v1/wchar.h:133:77: error: use of undeclared identifier 'wcschr'. wchar_t* __libcpp_wcschr(const wchar_t* __s, wchar_t __c) {return (wchar_t*)wcschr(__s, __c);}.                                                                             ^. /Users/sophiemarcotte/opt/miniconda3/bin/../include/c++/v1/wchar.h:140:87: error: use of undeclared identifier 'wcspbrk'. wchar_t* __libcpp_wcspbrk(const wchar_t* __s1, const wchar_t* __s2) {return (wchar_t*)wcspbrk(__s1, __s2);}.                                                                                       ^. /Users/sophiemarcotte/opt/miniconda3/bin/../include/c++/v1/wchar.h:147:78: error: use of undeclared identifier 'wcsrchr'; did you mean 'wcschr'?. wchar_t* __libcpp_wcsrchr(const wchar_t* __s, wchar_t __c) {return (wchar_t*)wcsrchr(__s, __c);}
i_answer: This seems to be a bug in LLVM. Try entering the command `xcode-select -p`. . . If you get something like `/Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer`, Xcode is configured to use developer tools instead of command line tools. To switch to the right one, enter the following command: . ```. sudo xcode-select -s /Library/Developer/CommandLineTools. ```

subject: "Run one system test"
content: Hello,. . I am curious as to what the "1c1, 23" means when we run the diff command in the "Run one system test" part of the setup. . . $ diff main_test.out main_test.out.correct. 1c1,23
i_answer: The number(s) to the left of the c is where the difference is on the 1st file and the number(s) to the right is where the difference is on the second file.. . The comma denotes all of the lines between the two numbers. This is saying that line 1 of main_test.out is different from lines 1-23 of main_test.out.correct. . . If two files are the same except for one line, line 3 for example, it would say 3c3.

subject: Mutating the vector and std utilities
content: Two questions:. . 1.   Given that the vectors are copied and a `sort` function is provided, is it safe to assume that we are permitted to mutate the vectors?. 2.   Are we permitted to use standard library utilities (e.g. `std::transform` or `std::accumulate`), as long as they are present in C++11?
i_answer: 1. Yes.. 2. You can only use the libraries listed in the spec.

subject: Guaranteed Presence of Data
content: Are we guaranteed that there will be at least one entry of data in every test/column or do we need to account for blank columns? If so, does that mean count, sum, etc. will all be 0?
i_answer: Great thinking! The constraints of the inputs and outputs are more clearly labeled as REQUIRES and EFFECTS respectively in the comments of each of the functions in stats.h  provided in the starter files. To answer your question directly though, you will need to account for an empty vector for count(). Most of the other functions require that the input vector is not empty, in which case you will not need to. You could always use assert() to verify the inputs of the functions follow the constraints of the requires clause which is considered good practice but not required.

subject: Downloading Files Issue (Windows)
content: I am having issues getting my files to download when I’m working in Ubuntu. First I am having issues creating the directory when using the cd command as I believe it says in the tutorial, as I keep getting told the directory doesn’t exist. This was the case when I had made a folder on my desktop and when that folder wasn’t there.
i_answer: The `cd` command is used to change directories / move between folders. The `mkdir` command is instead what you should use to make a directory (e.g. to make a folder called Downloads you would type `mkdir Downloads`. You could then move into that folder by `cd Downloads`)

subject: Trying to run test
content: When I try to run my test file executable this happens. Very scared pls help. I feel like my computer is mad at me.
i_answer: Essentially, your program crashed. Though the output looks a bit scary, this is actually the AddressSanitizer doing it's job by providing extra information about what caused the crash. If the output scares you, you can always edit your Makefile to remove the AddressSanitizer references that you added during the setup tutorial. The most important thing to look at here are the first couple lines, representing the order of functions that were called to lead to the crash. On line 43 of stats_test.cpp, the sum function was called. On line 22 of `stats.cpp` inside that sum function, your program crashed. Those might be locations to look at to find your bug.

subject: What are raise.c, abort.c, and assert.c?
content: I am trying to set up the debugger in VS Code, and I am running into a few errors, namely that it cannot locate some files. I will paste copies of the errors below, but do I need these files? If I don't need them, how do I stop the debugger from throwing this error, and if I do need them where do I get them?. . Copies of errors:. . Unable to open 'raise.c': Unable to read file 'vscode-remote://wsl+ubuntu/build/glibc-S9d2JN/glibc-2.27/sysdeps/unix/sysv/linux/raise.c' (Error: Unable to resolve non-existing file 'vscode-remote://wsl+ubuntu/build/glibc-S9d2JN/glibc-2.27/sysdeps/unix/sysv/linux/raise.c').. . Unable to open 'abort.c': Unable to read file 'vscode-remote://wsl+ubuntu/build/glibc-S9d2JN/glibc-2.27/stdlib/abort.c' (Error: Unable to resolve non-existing file 'vscode-remote://wsl+ubuntu/build/glibc-S9d2JN/glibc-2.27/stdlib/abort.c').. . Unable to open 'assert.c': Unable to read file 'vscode-remote://wsl+ubuntu/build/glibc-S9d2JN/glibc-2.27/assert/assert.c' (Error: Unable to resolve non-existing file 'vscode-remote://wsl+ubuntu/build/glibc-S9d2JN/glibc-2.27/assert/assert.c').. . Any help is appreciated!
i_answer: This error gets thrown when an assert fails in your code. VSCode is trying to step into the file where assert is defined, but it doesn't have the source code downloaded. You can just ignore this error, it won't cause issues with debugging.

subject: How to fix assertion failures? Trying to set up Valgrind on XCode on Mac
content: One of the prerequisites to setting up Valgrind is that your test compiles and runs without any assertion failures. As shown below, whenever I run "make clean" and then "make test" on my terminal, it shows that an assertion has failed. . . How do I fixed failed assertions?. .
i_answer: This is because as part of the setup tutorial, we have you insert placeholder code into `stats.cpp` where each function contains an `assert(false);`. To fix this, you could either: 1) remove the `assert(false);` lines by commenting them out (you may need to make each function return some dummy value as well, like 0 or an empty vector) or 2) wait to use Valgrind until you've implemented some / all of project 1.

subject: M1 Chip Mac Make Issue
content: I'm encountering a complier error saying that symbol not found for arm64. I searched for google, stackoverflow but got no answer. Could you offer some help? THX!.
i_answer: When you do an % ls to see what files are in your p1-stats directory, do you see stats_tests.cpp , stats.cpp, and p1_library.cpp listed? Usually, undefined symbol errors mean there was an issue linking the files during compile time (not necessarily anything wrong with your laptop configuration). If you do see those files listed though, what output do you get when you run % which g++? Hope this helps!
